post_text:
Horace Mann Elementary School teacher Lisa Everhart's kindergarten class has been learning about the alphabet by celebrating one new letter each day.
Everyday they read a rhyming book (from Frog Street Press) and learn a new song. The class creates a poster chart with pictures of the beginning sound. They create the letter with Play-Doh, connecting cubes, and traceable sand. They write the daily letter with their choice of a crayon, pencil, pen, dry erase marker, or smelly markers. For snack time, they try a “food tasting” that begins with the letter of the day.
One of the letters this week was “E" - so for snack time, students peeled their own hard-boiled eggs. It was a first-time experience for most of the students. Afterwards, they voted to see who liked or did not like eggs. 100 percent of the students said they LOVE hard boiled eggs!

During ELA class time on Team Apache at Sedalia Middle School, teacher Erica Shippman's students focused on their Flamin-Goals.
Her classroom is decorated in flamingos and pineapples, so Shippman used the "Flamin-Goals" as an Interactive Notebook project for Back To School. The students are keeping these goals in the front page of their Interactive ELA Notebooks as a reminder of their goals for the year.
"I can't wait to see what happens when the kiddos reflect back on their goals at the end of the year!," Shippman said.

post_text: In Smith-Cotton Junior High School teacher Michelle Steger's Project Lead the Way classes, the students did an activity called Saving Sam. Students had to work as a team and communicate to successfully "rescue Sam" from his capsized boat and put his lifejacket on him. They could only use 1 hand each and that hand had to be using a paperclip to manipulate the objects. Afterward, Steger and the students discussed what was difficult and how they can learn from this activity to communicate and work together as a team during the semester.

post_text: Students in Washington Elementary School second grade teacher Holly Redd's class completed the "paper chain challenge." They worked with partners to make the longest paper chain possible with one piece of construction paper and a time limit of 20 minutes. At the end of the 20 minutes, they compared the chains to see who made the longest one! It was an awesome team builder, and Redd said the students did an amazing job thinking outside the box and working together with a partner.

post_text:
To help address the statewide shortage of substitute teachers, the Missouri State Board of Education has approved an alternative route for individuals to obtain a substitute certificate of license to teach. Individuals who possess a high school diploma or equivalent may complete a 20-hour state-approved substitute teacher online training to be eligible for a substitute certificate. The training includes topics such as professionalism, honoring diversity, engaging students, foundational classroom management techniques, basic instructional strategies, supporting students with special needs, and working with at-risk youth.
In addition to completing the training, an applicant will be required to pass a background check and submit an application for their certificate.
For more information, go to https://dese.mo.gov/educator-quality/certification/substitute-teachers

During its Aug. 24 meeting, the Sedalia School District 200 Board of Education approved an amended resolution regarding the required use of face coverings by students and staff members. The resolution now states that masks and gaiter scarves that cover the nose and mouth are appropriate face coverings. Face shields are not acceptable.
Teachers may use face shields in limited time frames when curriculum requires them, but not as a replacement for masks generally.

post_text: Stanley Black & Decker Sedalia will donate all school supplies for every student at Washington Elementary School for the 2020-21 school year. The company became a community partner for the school at the start of the 2019-20 school year. Stanley Black & Decker Human Resources Manager LiShanna Bredehoeft said: "We know the students and staff will be facing several new challenges this year. We are proud and excited to be able to help them out while they navigate through these difficult times." Shown, from left, are Human Resources staff members Kari Wilson, Charli Darbyshire, Rufina Sultanov, Opie Petree and Janet David; Sedalia Plant Controller and Interim Plant Manage Brett Fox; and Bredehoeft. Washington Elementary Principal Lisa Volk said, "The support Washington receives from Stanley Black & Decker has been outstanding. We greatly appreciate the company's dedication to our students and staff members."

post_text:
Opinion Writing came to life for teacher Lisa Young's Summer School students, who will be entering fourth grade this fall.
The students read the book series "If You had Animal...Hair, Feet, Eyes, Teeth, Tails, Nose, and Ears." Students then chose the animal feature they thought would be the BEST to have and gave a reason why they chose that animal feature (their opinion). They had to support their opinion with evidence (a fact) from the text. Their writing came to life when they drew the animal feature on their own body. Writings were proudly displayed in the hall for others to read.

Sedalia 200 community,
Monday night's school board meeting, where return-to-school options will be discussed, will be live streamed on the district's YouTube channel. We will provide the link on the day of the event. Those in attendance who wish to address the board may do so; each speaker must identify themself and they have up to three minutes to share their thoughts.
If you will not be in attendance but would like to share your comments with the board, here are directions:
-- Send your comments via email to communications@sedalia200.org with the subject line "Comments for school board"
-- Limit your comments to 300 words or fewer
-- Include your full name
-- Deadline to submit comments via email is 5 pm Friday, July 24
Emailed comments will be shared with school board members before Monday's meeting.

post_text:
The Smith-Cotton High School High Voltage Dance Team had virtual camp with MA Dance Nation last week and learned some really fun choreography for performing season.

In addition to top awards for its team evaluations, S-C dancers earned a number of individual honors for outstanding work, attention, and mastery of choreography.

Rising Star award recipients: Anai Alejo, Marianne Treuner, and Sky Dennis

All-Star award recipients: Abby Caballero, Alyssa Ream, Ari Alonso, Courtney Balke, Emma Dillon, Madi Canon, and Teagan Berger
With this selection, these dancers have also earned All-American performance invitations to Macy's Thanksgiving Day parade and Citrus Bowl halftime.

Honor Roll award recipients: Emma Pettigrew, Envie Johnson, Faith Lewis, Lauren Grupe, Mya Fowler, and Rocio Castillo
These dancers earned a special pin after their initial selection for the All-Star award, an elite distinction of standout dancers at camp.

The Sedalia School District Foundation-Official will have its 14th Annual Golf Tournament fundraiser on June 29 at Sedalia Country Club. The event is sponsored by Dugan's Paint & Flooring Center.
In celebration of the foundation's 25th anniversary, Furnell Companies is sponsoring trick shot golf performer Dan Boever, from Springfield, at the tournament. Dan is the World Long Drive Champion and ranks among the most popular performers on the golf exhibition circuit. Whether blasting his driver 380 yards, hitting his putter 300 yards or taking aim at a drone high above the ground, he keeps the one-liners coming. Watch him in action at https://danboever.com/videos/
The foundation would love to have Sedalia School District #200 teachers and staff join them by becoming a sponsor, entering a golf team, or donating an item to the silent auction. Visit the SSDF website for forms and information at https://sedaliasdf.org/annual-golf-tournament/

post_text: Chancey Johnson, left, and Bryce Homan of M & R Monument Company install a memorial bench dedicated to former Sedalia School District 200 teacher and principal Brendan Eisenmenger on Thursday morning at the Memory Garden in front of Heber Hunt Elementary School. The bench was purchased by Heber Hunt staff through Payday Jeans Days, when staff can pay $10 to wear jeans to work. As a student, Johnson was in one of Eisenmenger's science classes and said he was glad to be involved in the memorial. Heber Hunt Principal Brett Hieronymus said, "There is no more fitting place for this tribute than the Memory Garden." Eisenmenger, who had been principal at Heber Hunt and later at Sedalia Middle School, passed away in November.

post_text:
Danny Watring, a 1981 Smith-Cotton High School graduate, is the latest inductee into the S-C Activities Hall of Fame. Watring was inducted in absentia as the induction and band concert scheduled earlier this month was canceled due to the coronavirus pandemic. Sadly, Watring passed away on May 24.
Watring taught instrumental music for 30 years before his retirement in 2016. His teaching career started and ended with Grandview schools. In between, he led or helped lead band programs at Liberty School District and Oak Park High School in the North Kansas City School District. He most recently served as adjunct professor of percussion and music education at Northwest Missouri State University in Maryville.
During his days at S-C, Watring earned All-District Band recognition three times and a Superior rating at the state Solo Festival twice. He received both the Louis Armstrong Jazz Award and the John Philip Sousa Band Award during his senior year.

To read his full Hall of Fame biography, go to https://www.sedalia200.org/site/default.aspx?PageID=187

Throughout her 25 years leading food service operations for the Sedalia 200 school district, Rowena Nickell always has kept students’ needs as her top priority.
Nickell, who was hired as the food service director in 1995, has announced her retirement, effective June 30. Debra Wenig, currently a district food service administrative assistant, has been named Nickell’s successor.
Assistant Superintendent Dr. Nancy Scott praised Nickell for her dedication to children and their nutritional needs.
“Rowena has such a big heart for kids and she has always created meals that are good and good for them,” Scott said. “She has been an exemplary leader and we thank her sincerely for her decades of service.”
Wenig, who has experience running meal services for church, preschool and day care operations, worked closely with Nickell the past two years.
“We are confident that Debbie will pick up where Rowena is leaving off. Her previous experience and time within our food service will help our program move forward seamlessly,” Scott said.

Smith-Cotton Junior High School teachers Mrs. Goalder, Ms. Dodge, Mrs. Caruthers, Mrs. Logan and the All Stars team students have been meeting on Zoom most Wednesdays and Fridays since distance learning started. On Friday, they played two truths and a lie. Teachers and students took turns sharing two truths and one lie about themselves. They took turns guessing what each person's lie was.
In previous weeks, they have done scavenger hunts, trivia or just socialized. Mrs. Goalder said, "It’s been nice maintaining social connections with our students. We have certainly missed them! We have had some “special guests” join us over the past several weeks. Shoutout to the elective teachers that have popped in to join our activities or visit with us!"

In closed session on Monday, May 11, the Sedalia School District 200 Board of Education approved Patrick Pyle as assistant principal at Heber Hunt Elementary School for the 2020-21 school year.
Pyle, currently a special education teacher at Sedalia Middle School, earned a bachelor of science degree in elementary education in May 2013 from Central Methodist University in Fayette. Earlier this month, he received his master’s degree in administration from William Woods University in Fulton.
Pyle joined the district as a paraprofessional in 2011, working at the Pettis County Early Childhood Center until 2013. He then served as a teacher at Washington Elementary through 2016, when he moved to his current role at the middle school.

post_text:
So many of our Sedalia 200 teachers and staff members are going the extra mile to remain engaged with their students while schools are closed. We will take time over the next few days and weeks to provide examples of those efforts.
Parkview Elementary fourth grade teacher Melissa Johnson has been delivering meals to students every day. She also has written each of her students a letter and continues to be pen pals with them, receiving letters almost daily and writing back to them.
"I am always so excited to see a letter from one of my students in my mailbox," she said.
Her students have been participating in many activities on Google Classroom as extra practice. She also has done many read alouds on Facebook live for Parkview's fourth grade students and has created Flipgrids for students to record videos.
"One flipgrid that I love is for reading fluency," Johnson said. "Students record themselves reading a book for about 90 seconds at a time and I listen and respond back."

Smith-Cotton High School biomedical students and members of HOSA Future Health Professionals recently had a Zoom video meeting with Dr. John Russel from Bothwell Internal Medicine. HOSA officers led the call and moderated a Q&A format covering topics from the basics of Coronavirus, specifics about how Bothwell and Sedalia have been affected, and general questions about his career in medicine.
Teacher and HOSA adviser Anna Singer said, " I was very proud of our HOSA officers who took on the leadership role on the video call. It was a unique opportunity and they did a great job."

It only takes a few minutes but the impact it has on your schools and your community is significant.

So many of our Sedalia 200 teachers and staff members are going the extra mile to remain engaged with their students while schools are closed. We will take time over the next few days and weeks to provide examples of those efforts.
Skyline Elementary kindergarten teacher Tina Emery has been reading books to her students via Facebook Live, including some of the "Piggie and Elephant" books. She also has done a phonics lesson and used a spinning wheel that contains sight words; Emery spins the wheel and students read the word, spell it and think of a sentence with that word in it.
Among her other activities with students last week were teaching a new letter and sight word, three-part drill (phonics program), read aloud and sight word review.
She also has been receiving mail from from her students and writing back to them.

post_text:
Message to Sedalia 200 seniors: We are canceling May 16th as our date for your graduation ceremony. The new date is 7 pm July 18th at the Mathewson Exhibition Center.
One of the biggest questions is “What will graduation look like?” We don't know at this time. We will hold to our two objectives for your graduation ceremony. The first will be your health and safety and the second will be giving you the opportunity to walk across the stage. To accomplish these objectives, we will work with local, state, and federal health officials as we near the July date. So at this time, we don't have more details.

Senior students and parents received information on other issues in an email sent this morning.

The students are excited to follow along and the parents have posted pictures and commented," Sherman said. "Ms. Maggie posted a picture of herself and her dog and asked others to do so. It was so much fun to see students and staff send in smiling pics with their pets."

By order of Gov. Mike Parson, all Missouri schools will remain closed for the rest of the 2019-20 academic year due to the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic. Schools have been encouraged to continue with remote learning strategies until the end of their district’s calendar for the current school year.
Sedalia #200 administrators are meeting to determine the best ways to finish out the balance of our school year for all grade levels. We will share our direction with you soon; grade-level Alternative Methods of Instruction will continue for the week of April 13-17 with emails going out to parents this weekend.
We thank our students, families, community and Sedalia #200 staff for their perseverance in these trying times. Our focus is unchanged: doing what is best for our students.

Parson’s stay-at-home executive order issued today regarding prevention of the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19), Sedalia School District #200’s current closure will be extended at least through Friday, April 24. We will not reopen schools until it is safe to do so for both our students and staff members.

post_text:
We are hopeful those who received meals today enjoyed them. There are a few key points we want to ensure are clear for our families:
-- Meals are free to any student, and no signup is required.
-- Students do NOT have to be accompanied by an adult to receive a meal bag.
-- First Student buses are delivering meals on the two-hour delayed start schedule. Example: If your child typically is picked up at 6:18 am, the bus will deliver meals at their stop at approximately 8:18 am.
-- Meals also can be picked up from 9:30 to 10:30 am at any of the district's 5 elementary schools, Sedalia Middle School or Smith-Cotton Junior High. Meals are not available at Whittier High or Smith-Cotton High - those students can pick up meal bags at any of the other schools.

post_text:
Just a reminder that Sedalia School District 200 and Heartland Redistribution Solutions and Support will provide free meals for students each weekday starting Monday, March 23. Meals will be delivered by First Student buses at regular bus stops on the two-hour delayed start schedule; students also can pick up meals at the school they attend from 9:30 to 10:30 am. Whittier High and Smith-Cotton High students can get meals at the school bus stops in their neighborhood or at nearby elementary schools, the middle school or junior high; meals will not be available for pickup at either high school. Co-op students can receive meals at bus stops or at a nearby school.
All students who request meals will be served. Children can receive meals but adults must be accompanied by a student to receive a meal package. To start, breakfast and lunch will be provided; there are plans to add dinner meals soon.

post_text:
Kendra Barton and Jerry Tankersley have been named assistant principals at Smith-Cotton High School for the 2020-21 school year. Their assignments were approved by the Sedalia School District 200 Board of Education in closed session Monday, March 9.
Barton and Tankersley replace current assistant principals Robin Wyatte, who is retiring at the end of the current school year, and Stacy Curry, who has been named principal of Smith-Cotton Junior High.
Smith-Cotton High Principal Wade Norton said: “Mr. Tankersley brings a wealth of academic experience to our team. His knowledge base with academics will allow us to continue to serve our students at the highest level. I am excited to watch him grow and connect with the students and staff in a new way. Ms. Barton coming to S-C allows us to quickly connect with our incoming freshman. Her administrative experience and experience at the junior high will bring Smith-Cotton new and fresh ideas.”

post_text:
Stacy Curry, currently an assistant principal at Smith-Cotton High School, has been named the principal at Smith-Cotton Junior High School effective at the end of the current school year. The promotion was approved by the Sedalia School District 200 Board of Education in closed session Monday, March 9.
Superintendent Steve Triplett said, “Ms. Curry has solid foundations in curriculum and administration. Her experience at the high school has prepared her well for this new challenge, which I know she will take on with professionalism and a student-centered mindset.”
Curry expressed her gratitude for the opportunity to support students who are in transitional years in their lives.
“I began my career as a junior high teacher and was held to a high standard,” she said. “I look forward to returning to the historic building and upholding the school’s high expectations, continuing the admirable work of my predecessors.”

post_text:
Brett Hieronymus, currently principal at Heber Hunt Elementary School, will become principal of Sedalia Middle School at the end of the current academic year. The move was approved by the Sedalia School District 200 Board of Education on Monday night.
Hieronymus is grateful for his time at Heber Hunt and is looking forward to this new opportunity.
“The district is experiencing some exciting changes and growth with the construction of the Loftus Early Childhood Center,” he said. “Sedalia Middle School is a special and unique place. Since SMS is focused on fifth grade, it is imperative to build relationships early and grow those connections to positively impact our students academically, socially and emotionally in the time we have them.”

post_text: Washington Elementary kindergartners on Monday reviewed How-to stories in their writing unit. They came up with the steps and tried to follow the directions to make a peanut butter and jelly sandwich. They soon learned that a few important steps were missing so they went back and added more details, evaluated their work and added pictures to help with following the steps. The students have learned transitional words, and diagrams to help the reader better understand their how-to stories.

Smith-Cotton High School senior Emily Beltran has received an academic scholarship and will perform with the competitive dance team at Central Methodist University in Fayette.

post_text: Last week, Horace Mann Elementary - Sedalia, MO teacher Danielle Gerke's class learned about dinosaurs. They focused on fossils and their importance Friday. Students learned that without fossils we wouldn’t be able to learn about dinosaurs since they are extinct. Students watched a video of how a paleontologist carefully digs out the bone pieces. Then students got to practice by excavating the chocolate chips from their cookie.

The Parents As Teachers program will offer free developmental screenings for children age 3 months to 5 years on March 11-12 at the Pettis County Early Childhood Cooperative, 2255 S. Ingram Ave. Screening times are 3:30, 4:45, or 6 p.m.
Screenings are by appointment only and eligible children must be residents of Pettis County and not yet in kindergarten. The areas screened include speech, vision, hearing, language, readiness and motor skills; there also is a health questionnaire.
To schedule an appointment and for more information, call the co-op at 660-827-8955. Time slots are filling up fast.

Smith-Cotton Show Choirs New Score and Vocal Velocity competed at the Heart of America Competition in Kansas City on February 29. Vocal Velocity placed third out of the prep and unisex groups. New Score qualified for finals and placed fourth runner-up overall.

This competition brought their competitive season to a close very successfully. Director Bryce Hesterman said, "They grew each week as they went out and performed and were able to leave their best performances on the stage today."

post_text: Nine Smith-Cotton High School seniors participated Wednesday in a live enlistment ceremony in conjunction with the U.S. Army and the International Space Station. The enlistees gathered in the Heckart Performing Arts Center along with Smith-Cotton JROTC cadets and other students to watch an international broadcast from the space station. U.S. Army Col. Andrew Morgan, currently aboard the space station, administered the oath of office through technology then answered some pre-arranged questions about his military career and life aboard the ISS. Taking the oath were Sarah Bradbury, Autumn Bauer and Evan Meloy, U.S. Army National Guard; Bethany Rogers and Isaiah Robinson, U.S. Air Force; and Alexis Carey, Abrianna Barnett, Ty-Kristofer King and Dalton Turner, U.S. Marine Corps.

post_text:
Recently, Sedalia Middle School Science classes did the perfect activity to illustrate the nature of food chains and to demonstrate the role of predators in the ecosystem. Students got to dissect an owl pellet. This hands-on activity paired well with the curriculum unit on energy and matter in ecosystems. This activity helped the students understand how energy and matter moves through an ecosystem.
Teacher Lindsey Benbrook explained, "Owls usually swallow their food whole, digest the edible parts, and then regurgitate the indigestible parts through their mouth as a pellet. Using tweezers (and perhaps a magnifying glass), the students examined the inside of the barn owl pellets to discover the bones (or indigestible parts) of critters that are eaten by barn owls. The students found jawbones, skulls, and other fascinating bits and pieces. Bone identification and bone sorting of their discoveries helped them to further understand the different animals in a barn owl's food chain. The students loved it!"

post_text: Great shout-out at Parkview Elementary!
shared_text:
Parkview Elementary
February 13 at 4:54 PM ·

One of my students looked out the window and noticed our custodian was outside shoveling the snow off our sidewalks. He raised his hand and said, “Look at Mr. Richard out there taking care of us! He’s just the best! Can I stop and type him a note to tell him thank you?” Well, what’s a gal going to say to that? It took all I could do to not shed tears at his thoughtfulness and that this kid 1) noticed 2) wanted to acknowledge our hardworking custodian for his efforts, & 3) typed the sweetest note of appreciation! After asking if he could type a note, three others noticed Mr. Richard too and wrote notes too! Once class was over, we scurried down to the cafeteria and posted the notes of appreciation on his board! - - Mrs. Darla Lansing #pricelessmoments #daymade #teacherslife #pkvproud @parkviewtigers #kindnessmatters

On Saturday Feb. 8, the Smith-Cotton Show Choirs competed at Harrisonville High School’s Show Choir Competition. Vocal Velocity (shown in file photo) took first in the mixed prep division while New Score took third in the 5A division. New Score qualified for finals and received fifth runner-up overall.
S-C Director of Vocal Music Bryce Hesterman said: "It was a good day for the students to see where they are at as well as improve upon things for the future. We look to keep this momentum moving forward into next weekend when we travel to Nevada."

post_text:
Sedalia Middle School art teacher Kelly Hagen had her students incorporate some Asian culture into a recent project.
"I'm always wanting to culturally expand my students," Hagen said. "This year Chinese New Year Zodiac is the year of the rat. We learned how this is one of the biggest celebrations in China, also called Lunar New Year or Spring festival. That's why some contain a moon and the purpose of the cherry blossom branch. We used Ink to paint to mimic Chinese calligraphy, We finger painted to make the flowers. We researched Chinese folklore. The rat was a study on contour line drawing, which the kids excelled at."

January 31 at 3:00 PM ·

Alumni Spotlight: Philip Ximinies ‘19 has started his career teaching at Sedalia Middle School. Featured below is a picture of him on the first day of school dressed as a mad scientist. He explained to his students that he would be their science teacher and they would learn a number of interesting things about science.

Philip is also pictured below with a couple of his co-workers. When speaking with one of his co-workers, Roxy Himes, to gain some insight on Philip as a teacher she said, “ He’s always eager to try new things and jump in to help whenever possible. His colleagues respect and value him. He is building relationships with his students and they all love him. He invests himself in his students and strives to help them succeed. He’s already impacting student’s lives and I have no doubt he will continue to do so.”

post_text:
Sedalia School District 200 has a free smartphone app to enhance communication between the district, its parents and the community.
The app, created by Blackboard, can be downloaded from the App Store on iPhones and through Google Play on non-Apple phones; just search for Sedalia 200 and it should come up. Once installed, the user selects the buildings he or she is interested in following. That’s it – it’s ready to use.
The app allows users to see our most recent social media posts, check meal menus at all schools, tap into the Parent Portal and check the district calendar. There also is a directory for each Sedalia 200 building.
STUDENTS AND COMMUNITY MEMBERS: In cases of inclement weather delays or school cancellations, we post to the app at the same time that we send text, email and phone messages to parents.

Students in Horace Mann teacher Lisa Everhart's kindergarten class are getting ready to study about 2-D and 3-D shapes.
They took the opportunity to activate their prior knowledge and to use snap cubes to build familiar or new creative structures in teams of two.
First, students had to discuss their idea with each other. Then, they had to build their own individual structure.

On Thursday, Jan. 9, Officer Lorenz from the Sedalia Police Department and his K-9, Charlie, visited Parkview Elementary third graders. Students read the story “Aero and Officer Mike” this week and were eager to see a real dog in action.
Officer Lorenz discussed how he trained Charlie, how the department uses him, and answered many student questions. The highlight was when Charlie could "sniff" out the correct box. It was both a treat for Charlie and the students.

Spring 2020 FIT Internship Info: Internships are available in February, March, April, and May (seniors only). Applications are due a month prior so plan ahead. Students must be a junior or senior, with no D or F grades, good attendance, and no discipline issues.

What is a FIT Internship?
-- A chance to learn about a career of the student's choice
-- Work with an employer during the school day for a week
-- Student finds out if they like the work

For students interested in a FIT Internship in February, applications are due by Wednesday, Jan. 22. See Mrs. Harvey in Room D113 with questions.
